Astronaut

Target IP: 192.168.170.12

Scanning


There are only two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The webpage above is displayed for this application. After performing directory search, I did not find anything useful. I tried to obtain the version application, but I had no luck.


I did find the login page at /admin, but it wanted the login details -- which I didn't have. I tried spraying different default credentials, such as admin:admin, but I had no luck. The /cgi-bin is also returned. However, doing a directory search against this directory for sh scripts did not yield anything useful.

Exploitation


Apparently the CMS used by the target machine is vulnerable to RCE, according to the article above. This article is available at https://www.rapid7.com/db/modules/exploit/linux/http/gravcms_exec/. Time to run this exploit against the target.


I used the exploit /linux/http/gravcms_exec. The picture above contains the parameters set for the exploit. I changed three values: RHOSTS, TARGETURI, and LHOST.


After initialising the parameters, I ran the exploit and I had success! I gained a reverse shell connection.

Privilege Escalation


The file admin.yaml contains the credentials of the user admin. I obtained the password hash
$2y$10$dlTNg17RfN4pkRctRm1m2u8cfTHHz7Im.m61AYB9UtLGL2PhlJwe. of user admin. While enumerating, I ran john to decrypt the password.


Running find / -perm -u=s 2>/dev/null shows /usr/bin/php7.4 has SUID bit enabled!


And now I am root. GG.
